[ProMED thanks
- Dr. Roland Hubner, Scientific Collaborator, FPS Public Health,
Brussels, for also providing this same report;
- Naomi Bryant, Information Officer, National Travel Health Network
and Centre, United Kingdom, who sent a similar Euro WHO report:
(<http://www.euro.who.int/surveillance/outbreaks/20070904_1>);
- ProMED Rapporteur Mary Marshall who provided a similar Reuters report:
(<http://www.alertnet.org/services/alerting/breakingnews_adv.htm?channel_id=-1&path=%2Fthenews%2Fnewsdesk%2FL06891045.htm>
registration required); and
- Dr. Giuseppe Michieli <gimi69@libero.it>, who provided case numbers.
The outbreak has attracted much attention as the first autochthonous
chikungunya virus outbreak in Europe. As the WHO/Euro report (cited
above) states, "Given the presence of the competent vector documented
in at least 12 European countries (Albania, Italy, France, Belgium,
Montenegro, Switzerland, Greece, Spain, Croatia, the Netherlands,
Slovenia & Bosnia-Herzegovina) as well as favourable climatic
conditions for the vector to persist in the coming few months in the
Mediterranean basin, countries should remain vigilant for the
emergence of this infectious disease."
The same can be said for other countries harboring _Aedes albopictus_
or _Ae. aegypti_, such as those in the Americas.
A map of the Emilia Romagna region and its location in Italy can be accessed at
<http://www.knowital.com/italy/maps/emiliaromagnamap.html>. - Mod.TY]
